amid soaring health spending there is growing interest in workplace disease prevention and wellness programs to improve health and lower costsin a critical metaanalysis of the literature on costs and savings associated with such programs we found that medical costs fall by about 327 for every dollar spent on wellness programs and that absenteeism costs fall by about 273 for every dollar spentalthough further exploration of the mechanisms at work and broader applicability of the findings is needed this return on investment suggests that the wider adoption of such programs could prove beneficial for budgets and productivity as well as health outcomes